oai_qdc:qualifieddc.dc:title: Obey River
oai_qdc:qualifieddc.dc:description: Logging and rafting at the mouth of the Obey River, which flows into the Cumberland River.
The Obey River is a 47.8-mile-long tributary of the Cumberland River. One of the first permanent settlers in Clay County was Obediah Terrill, who arrived about 1770. The Obey River is named for him.
oai_qdc:qualifieddc.dc:source: Looking Back at Tennessee Photograph Collection, 1890-1981
